docs.abstract: The $4.5 billion in emergency funds would help federal agencies deal with an influx of migrants and asylum seekers at the Mexican border.
docs.snippet: The $4.5 billion in emergency funds would help federal agencies deal with an influx of migrants and asylum seekers at the Mexican border.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House asked Congress on Wednesday to allocate $4.5 billion in emergency funds for the southwestern border as federal agencies struggle to house and cope with the influx of asylum seekers coming into the United States.

headline.main: White House Asks Congress for Billions More in Border Funding
headline.print_headline: White House Asks for $4.5 Billion to Cope With Wave of Migrants at Border

byline.original: By Emily Cochrane and Zolan Kanno-Youngs

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Arrests at the southwestern border dropped by 28 percent in June, according to the Department of Homeland Security, signaling the first time this year that the number of border crossings declined.

headline.main: Border Arrests Drop by 28% in June in First Decline of the Year
headline.print_headline: Officials Say Arrests Fell By 28 Percent At the Border

docs.abstract: The flagship industry in a pivotal swing state faces an economic crisis.
docs.snippet: The flagship industry in a pivotal swing state faces an economic crisis.
docs.lead_paragraph: KENDALL, Wis. — For decades, Denise and Tom Murray rose before 5 a.m. and shuffled through mud and snow to milk cows on the farm that has been in their family since 1939. This month, after years of falling milk prices and mounting debt, the Murrays sold their last milk cow, taking pictures while holding back tears as the final one was loaded onto a truck and taken away.

headline.main: Stung by Trump’s Trade Wars, Wisconsin’s Milk Farmers Face Extinction

docs.abstract: Shortly after dropping a threat of tariffs against Mexico, the Trump administration showed no inclination to back down in its dispute with Beijing.
docs.snippet: Shortly after dropping a threat of tariffs against Mexico, the Trump administration showed no inclination to back down in its dispute with Beijing.
docs.lead_paragraph: FUKUOKA, Japan — Global finance leaders meeting in Japan this weekend said they were increasingly worried that the trade dispute between the United States and China, which shows no signs of abating, could propel the world economy into a crisis.

headline.main: World Economic Leaders Warn of Fallout From Trade War Between U.S. and China
headline.print_headline: At G-20 Meeting, U.S.-China Trade Dispute Sours Global Economic Outlook

docs.abstract: Though presidential candidates appearing at a debate on Tuesday generally favored a strong approach to China, they differed over whether protectionism was the way forward.
docs.snippet: Though presidential candidates appearing at a debate on Tuesday generally favored a strong approach to China, they differed over whether protectionism was the way forward.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Democratic presidential candidates clashed in a Tuesday night debate over how they would change course from President Trump’s protectionist trade agenda in fiery exchanges that underscored the depth of the rift within the party over economic policy.

headline.main: Echo Trump’s Tough Talk, or Lift Tariffs? Democrats Clash Over Trade
headline.print_headline: Democrats Struggle to Find Firm Footing to Confront the President on Trade

docs.abstract: Economists say the Treasury secretary, whose comments dovetail with those of President Trump, is turning a blind eye to signs of a slowdown.
docs.snippet: Economists say the Treasury secretary, whose comments dovetail with those of President Trump, is turning a blind eye to signs of a slowdown.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin said on Monday that President Trump’s tariffs on Chinese imports were having no impact on the United States economy, an assertion that was at odds with a raft of increasingly gloomy economic data and industry surveys.

headline.main: Mnuchin Dismisses Data Showing Trade War Pain
headline.print_headline: Mnuchin Dismisses Data Showing Trade War Pain

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Friday said he had not yet agreed to roll back any of the tariffs he had imposed on China and that, if a deal is reached, he would not eliminate all of the levies he’s placed on $360 billion worth of goods.

headline.main: Trump Rules Out Complete Rollback of China Tariffs as Talks Continue
headline.print_headline: President Rules Out Complete Rollback of Tariffs on China as Talks Continue

docs.abstract: The Treasury secretary also said that President Trump will meet with China’s leader, Xi Jinping, at the G-20 leaders’ summit in Osaka, Japan, later this month.
docs.snippet: The Treasury secretary also said that President Trump will meet with China’s leader, Xi Jinping, at the G-20 leaders’ summit in Osaka, Japan, later this month.
docs.lead_paragraph: FUKUOKA, Japan — The icy relationship between the United States and China over trade showed no signs of easing on Saturday, as Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin called on Beijing to return to talks and follow through on its commitments or face more tariffs from President Trump.

headline.main: Mnuchin Lays Blame for Failed Trade Talks on China
headline.print_headline: Mnuchin Puts Blame For Impasse On Beijing

docs.abstract: International deals involving technology and real estate could be blocked under proposed new rules that would add teeth to a law passed last year.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration proposed new rules on Tuesday that would allow the United States to exert greater control over foreign investment by broadening the government’s authority to block technology and real estate transactions.

headline.main: U.S. Outlines Plans to Scrutinize Chinese and Other Foreign Investment
headline.print_headline: U.S. Plans Tighter Rules On Foreign Investment

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Democratic congressional leaders emerged from a meeting at the White House on Tuesday and announced that President Trump had agreed to pursue a $2 trillion infrastructure plan to upgrade the nation’s highways, railroads, bridges and broadband.

headline.main: Trump and Democrats Agree to Pursue $2 Trillion Infrastructure Plan
